<div id="comment_status_64128043" class="commentstatus"></div>
<div id="comment_64128043" class="cw">
	<div id="comment_top_64128043" class="commentTop newcomment">
		<div class="title">
			<h4><a id="comment_link_64128043" name="comment_link_64128043" href="//news.slashdot.org/comments.pl?sid=23180677&amp;cid=64128043" onclick="return D2.setFocusComment(64128043)" >Unsubstantiated? Seriously?</a>


		 	<span id="comment_score_64128043" class="score"> (<a href="#" onclick="getModalPrefs('modcommentlog', 'Moderation Comment Log', 64128043); return false"><span class=opt>Score:</span>3</a>)</span></h4>
		</div>
		<div class="details">
			<span class="by"><span class="byby">by </span><a href="//slashdot.org/~Torodung">Torodung</a>  <span class="uid"><a href="//slashdot.org/~Torodung">( 31985 )</a></span></a></span><span class="writes" style="display:none"> writes:</span> 
			<span class="otherdetails" id="comment_otherdetails_64128043">		
		on Wednesday January 03, 2024 @12:27PM (<span class="ind"></span><a href="//news.slashdot.org/comments.pl?sid=23180677&amp;cid=64128043">#64128043</a>)
		<small><a href="//slashdot.org/~Torodung/journal/" title="Sunday September 14, 2008 @04:13PM" class="user_journal_display">Journal</a> </small>
</span>
		</div>
	</div>
	<div class="commentBody">
		<div id="comment_body_64128043"><p>Regarding the addictive potential, this is basic neurochemistry 101 not a puritanical, trumped-up guess.</p><p>It's a dopamine hit. It's the same reason people get addicted to slots, gacha pulls, or even likes on Facebook. It is well documented.</p><p>For people with a neurodivergent vulnerability to dopamine bursts, it can definitely become an issue and eventually a problem. That's one good reason for an age limit. It's also a good reason for a strictly enforced engagement time limit. These systems should shut people out when it's clear they're abusing them as a drug.</p><p>Pornhub just doesn't want to increase its operating expenses by complying with absolutely sane restrictions that apply to minors in similar activities. They know exactly what they're doing and they don't want to pay the safety costs. The law sure didn't ban it. Pornhub did by not bothering to comply. It's greed.</p><p>As for the Facebook and gacha, well, we really should do something about that, don't you think? Those companies have ethically compromised psychiatry professionals on staff trying to get the dopamine dosage just right for maximum engagement. That's what's sick, not the pr0n.</p><p><i>Always gamble responsibly.</i></p></div>
	</div>

	<div class="commentSub" id="comment_sub_64128043">
